Mystery solved: That&#39;s why we can&#39;t tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebrum prevents people from tickling themselves. Scientists at the Humboldt University in Berlin found this out with the help of experiments on rats, as they announced on Thursday evening. Progress has also been made on why children resist tickling so fiercely only to then ask for more.
Finally, it has also been shown why the mere approach of a tickling hand triggers laughter even before it is touched. This is due to a deep layer in the cerebrum that triggers laughter as soon as you expect to be tickled.
According to the information, previous research showed that rats respond with ultrasonic &quot;laughing&quot; when tickled by humans. This &quot;laughing&quot; is mediated by the part of the cerebral cortex that serves the central processing of haptic perception.
Laughter is suppressed during self-touch
So far it has been assumed that the brain can distinguish between self-touch and touch by others - that is why people cannot tickle themselves. However, the Berlin researchers found out in the experiments on the rats that laughter and the activity of the relevant area of the cerebral cortex are suppressed during self-touching. This is also the case when living beings clean themselves. During the touching and tickling by the scientists, however, the activity in the brain and the impulse to laugh were intensified.
But if the self-touch and the touch of others happen at the same time, the laughter is also suppressed. This indicates that the rat brain cannot differentiate between touching itself and being touched by others. The new findings suggested that people cannot tickle themselves because self-touching activates a brake in the cerebrum.
The rats were also trained to tickle themselves. In doing so, they sometimes broke off this initiation prematurely in the experiment, showed flight behavior or were terrified. This ambivalence resembles the behavior of children. The ambivalence of tickling is a behavioral response that is the same in rats and humans.
