Caution: NEVER charge your smartphone wirelessly
Convenient but harmful
Although inductive technology via the Qi standard is extremely practical, it should not be used.
Since several new smartphones have recently come onto the market that support wireless charging and are selling very well - above all the new iPhone 11 models, we would like to recall a study from the beginning of July. Wireless charging of mobile devices is extremely practical, but not necessarily recommended.
Higher temperatures clog the battery
Researchers warn against wireless charging of smartphones. According to the findings of the University of Warwick, this is extremely harmful to the devices. The reason for this is the significantly greater heat development. If you charge a cell phone normally with a cable, the battery heats up to 27 degrees within three hours. With wireless charging, however, the researchers always measured more than 30 degrees, even when the smartphone was perfectly aligned on the charging pad. If the mobile phone is slightly next to the coil, the temperature rises even higher. In addition, the wattage of the charging pad also increases, which in turn drives up power consumption.
capacity and lifetime
According to the researchers, temperature is a key factor in battery life. Every single degree plays a role. When charging at higher temperatures, the battery not only loses capacity, it also doesn&#39;t last as long overall. The service life is therefore shorter. The researchers therefore recommend always charging the smartphone with a cable. Since replacing the battery in modern smartphones is always associated with high costs, this should be a helpful tip. Apple recently increased the cost of replacing the battery again - for all iPhones.
Practical
The technology is extremely convenient: Simply place the device on an appropriate charging pad - these are now even installed in many restaurants, airports, hotels and cars - and the battery is charged without the hassle of tangled cables and laborious plug fumbling. Since Qi (stands for inductive energy transfer) is a worldwide standard that even Apple takes part in exceptionally, there are hardly any restrictions. Nevertheless, according to the researchers, the technology should only be used in exceptional cases.
