Comet from another star crosses the solar system
Astronomers are currently observing a comet from deep space. That worked once before. The comet allows conclusions to be drawn about other solar systems.
What was initially just a guess has now been confirmed: an interstellar guest is crossing our solar system. The deep-space comet, named 2I/Borisov after its discoverer, has attracted the interest of astronomers around the world.
The well-traveled comet was discovered on August 30 by amateur astronomer Gennady Borissow at the Margo Observatory in Crimea - with a homemade telescope with a diameter of 65 centimeters. Follow-up observations from various observatories not only confirmed that it is an unknown comet, but also showed that it did not come from our solar system.
2I/Borisov is only the second interstellar object sighted during a transit of our solar system, after 1I/&#39;Oumuamua from 2017.
2I/Borisov offers astronomers a rare chance to get an up-close look at an alien solar system before it vanishes, never to be seen again. First observations show that the interstellar comet resembles those of our own system, as reported by the Canary Islands Astrophysical Institute. &quot;The current speed of the comet is high, about 150,000 kilometers per hour, which is well above the typical speeds of objects orbiting the sun at this distance,&quot; said Davide Farnocchia of the US space agency Nasa in a statement.
According to the analyzes, the comet is on a so-called hyperbolic orbit, which leads it out of our system - and is clearly of interstellar origin, as the International Astronomical Union (IAU) announced. She is also responsible for naming and categorizing celestial bodies. In honor of its discoverer, the interstellar tail star, which was initially listed under the catalog number C/2019 Q4, was given the designation 2I/Borisov, with the first part of the name indicating that it is the second interstellar object to be discovered discovered in our solar system.
The astronomers are lucky: In contrast to 1I/&#39;Oumuamua, 2I/Borisov was already sighted on approach. This gives the researchers many months for investigations. &quot;The object will reach its greatest brightness in mid-December and can then be seen with medium-sized telescopes until April 2020,&quot; explained Farnocchia. &quot;After that, it will only be observable with larger, professional telescopes until October 2020.&quot;
Several observatories have already targeted the visitor. A team led by Karen Meech from the University of Hawaii, who had already led the characterization of 1I/&#39;Oumuamua, determined the diameter of the celestial object to be between 2 and 16 kilometers in an initial study. Images from the Gemini Observatory in Hawaii show a clear tail of the comet.
Researchers at the Canary Islands Astrophysical Institute (IAC) have already obtained a first so-called spectrum from the interstellar tail star, which offers a kind of fingerprint of its chemical composition. &quot;The spectrum of this object is similar to that of comets in our solar system, and this indicates that their composition must be similar,&quot; reported IAC researcher Julia de León. This observation suggests that comets in other solar systems could form through processes similar to ours, added de León&#39;s colleague Javier Licandro.
According to the IAU, the discovery of two interstellar visitors within just two years indicates that these objects could open up a new way of studying certain processes in other solar systems. However, it is still difficult to estimate how frequent such flying visits are. A planned satellite mission by the European space agency Esa could possibly intercept one of the next interstellar visitors.
The agency wants to station the three-part &quot;Comet Interceptor&quot; spacecraft in a holding position 1.5 million kilometers from Earth by 2028. According to ESA Science Director Günther Hasinger, it should either be lurking for an untouched, fresh comet from our own solar system, or for an interstellar visitor like 1I/&#39;Oumuamua.
