Half of the European tree species are threatened with extinction
In addition to pests, diseases, non-native species, unsustainable logging and urban growth are also causes of the threat, the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) reported on Friday in Brussels. She examined the stocks of all 454 tree species known in Europe. 265 of them do not occur on any other continent. Of these 265, 58 percent are threatened. 66 would already be at the highest level of endangerment and thus on the verge of extinction.
The IUCN classifies endangered species into six categories: from &quot;Near Threatened&quot; to &quot;Vulnerable&quot;, &quot;Endangered&quot;, &quot;Critically Endangered&quot; and &quot;Extinct in the wild&quot; to &quot;Extinct&quot;. In total, it lists more than 28,000 animal and plant species worldwide as endangered.
Mountain ash and wild horse chestnut threatened
In Germany, rowan trees (Sorbus) are particularly threatened, said one of the authors, David Allen, of the German Press Agency. &quot;Most are threatened because populations are small anyway, or through conversion or degradation of their habitats.&quot;
Things are also looking bad for the wild horse chestnuts. They have been classified as &quot;Vulnerable&quot;, level two on the IUCN scale, since 2017. Besides a fungus, the biggest threat is the Balkan leaf miner. It has been spreading from south-eastern Europe across the entire continent since the 1980s and has hardly any natural enemies. IUCN estimates the number of wild horse chestnut trees (Aesculus hippocastanum) in Europe at fewer than 10,000 specimens. Trees in cities, parks and avenues are not taken into account in this assessment.
Shrub species and mosses are also at risk
At the same time, IUCN scientists produced new European Red Lists for molluscs, shrubs and mosses. More than a fifth of mollusks and mosses and almost half of all shrub species are threatened, according to the IUCN. This is mainly due to the destruction of wilderness, introduced species, agricultural practices and climate change. Mollusks such as snails play a key role in recycling nutrients in the soil and are an important food source for birds and other animals.
&quot;This report shows that the situation is precarious for many overlooked and underestimated species, species that form the backbone of Europe&#39;s ecosystem and contribute to a healthy planet,&quot; said Luc Bas, IUCN Director of the Europe Office. &quot;We must limit human impact on our ecosystems and make protecting these species a priority.&quot;
