Misleading - according to the President, that is what the other man who currently determines what is happening on the streets is trying to do. Mohamed Ali, of course, remained abroad, evading the reach of the security forces, who would arrest him immediately if he tried to set foot on Egyptian soil. Weeks ago, the 45-year-old actor was only known to a minority of Egyptians. Today he is the leading voice that dominates the political discourse in the country&#39;s cafés, living rooms and tea rooms: With his YouTube channel &quot;Mohamed&#39;s Secrets,&quot; Ali calls on his compatriots to rise up against Sisi.
He addresses the head of state directly and in quite rustic language. While the people are starving, the president is wallowing in luxury and having magnificent new palaces built, it says. Ali accuses the army leadership, on which Sisi bases his rule, of corruption and enrichment. Because he did business with these very gentlemen in his second job as a building contractor for 15 years, he seems to know pretty well what he&#39;s talking about - at least that&#39;s the impression many Egyptians have, as the exploding number of clicks shows.
After thousands of people demonstrated against his rule last week for the first time since Sisi took power and almost 2,000 citizens, including prominent figures from civil society, human rights lawyers and opposition politicians, were arrested, Ali called for a &quot;million march&quot; for this Friday. It was unlikely that so many people would dare to take to the streets. But there were isolated smaller protests, for example in Giseh near Cairo and in the town of Kina near Luxor. Videos on social media showed protests in which participants accused al-Sisi of corruption and called for his departure. During these protests, police also used tear gas and rubber bullets. Initially, these videos could not be independently verified. Security sources said the police had ended the protests.
A heavy police presence was reported on Friday in the Nile Delta city of Mansura, where demonstrators tore up banners bearing the president&#39;s portrait last week. Security forces set up checkpoints in the city and on arterial roads. In Cairo, several downtown subway stations have been closed for &quot;maintenance work,&quot; and most roads around Tahrir Square, the heart of the 2011 revolution, have been blocked. And on Rabaa Square, where supporters of the toppled Muslim Brotherhood Morsi holed up in 2013 until the army fired on them and killed up to 800 people, another measure was intended to prevent dissatisfied people from gathering: Sisi&#39;s future party wanted a major rally here of all places hold for the President.
These precautions prompted Mohamed Ali to change his tactics: &quot;Our goal doesn&#39;t have to be Tahrir Square,&quot; Ali said into his video camera in Barcelona. &quot;Let&#39;s not clash with police officers&quot;. But that shouldn&#39;t be understood as a retreat: &quot;The whole of Egypt is Tahrir Square.&quot;
If the provider promises too much performance
If the Internet connection always seems much slower than advertised by the provider, there are various test options.
Anyone who concludes an Internet contract does not need to blindly trust the speed information provided by the provider. In the event of anomalies, customers can check for themselves how much of this has actually been achieved.
After all, the transmission rates promised in advance are part of the contract and should therefore also be achieved, explains the Bavarian consumer advice center.
If the connection always seems much slower than advertised by the provider, there are various test options. The measuring tools of the Federal Network Agency (BNetzA) measure the actual data transmission rates and compare them with the rate agreed in the contract.
&quot;However, the provider tests are carried out according to provider-specific specifications and are therefore not calculated uniformly and objectively,&quot; the Bavarian consumer advice center points out.
If the connection is significantly slower than announced, customers can give the provider a reasonable period of usually 14 days to provide the promised service. The best way to do this is in writing by registered mail.
If this does not work even after repeated requests, customers can cancel and possibly also claim damages. But if there is no success, the only way to go is to take legal action.
