Influencer wants free upgrade: Lifetime flight ban at Cathay
Allegedly, Jaqueline Ng was promised an upgrade by email from Cathay Pacific. But when she asked for it at check-in, she was not allowed on board - and she should never be allowed to fly with Cathay again.
Getting an upgrade to Business Class on the spur of the moment - that&#39;s what many passengers dream of. Sometimes they are lucky and the check-in staff will offer a free transfer from Economy Class.
However, this case shows how not to do it: A self-declared influencer actively asked the airline Cathay Pacific for a free upgrade. More than 65,000 users follow Jaqueline Ng on Instagram. She flew from Taiwan to New York on May 30th and back on June 7th.
On the outward flight, the staff refused Jaqueline an upgrade, even though she had shown an email in which Cathay Pacific allegedly offered her the prospect of an upgrade. The influencer claims to have received the letter from a marketing employee of the airline. The airline, on the other hand, accuses Jaqueline of forging the email.
On the return flight, Jaqueline tried again to get an upgrade for the long-haul flight. This time the woman is said to have shown the same email, but with a different reference number. The employees at JFK airport were skeptical: they checked with the head office. And in fact, the employee who allegedly sent the email denied having email contact with Jaqueline. This was also confirmed by the mail system, in which the messages did not appear.
Airline officials at the airport canceled Jaqueline&#39;s ticket and issued a lifetime flight ban on Cathay Pacific. She had to buy a new plane ticket to Taiwan for 1,400 US dollars (around 1,280 euros).
The influencer turned to Elliot Advocacy, a company that represents consumer interests, with her case. Because Cathay had reimbursed her the price of her original ticket, but Jaqueline also claimed back the cost of the new ticket.
But as long as Jaqueline does not submit the metadata of the mail, the case remains clear: the influencer committed fraud for Cathay, she remains blocked for future flights. The airline&#39;s terms and conditions also state that it does not have to pay for the new flight. Jaqueline doesn&#39;t want to be satisfied with that - and is now hiring a lawyer.
Oil prices fall after Yemen ceasefire report
Oil prices fell by more than a dollar in a very short space of time on Friday afternoon. Most recently, a barrel (159 liters) of the North Sea Brent cost 61.83 US dollars - around 1.4 percent less than the day before. The price of a barrel of the American West Texas Intermediate (WTI) variety fell by 1.3 percent to $55.77.
The trigger for the price slide was a Wall Street Journal report on a ceasefire in Yemen. Saudi Arabia is said to have agreed to a ceasefire in four areas.
A drone attack on the oil facilities in Saudi Arabia in mid-September brought five percent of global oil production to a standstill. The Houthi rebels, allied with Iran in civil war Yemen, claimed responsibility for the attacks. Like the US government, Saudi Arabia blames Iran. A ceasefire would defuse political tension in the region.
If an agreement is reached, the focus can be on growth and demand concerns, Ole Hansen, head of commodity strategy at Saxo Bank, told Bloomberg.
Oil prices are continuing their downward movement of the past few days. A week ago, a barrel of WTI oil cost almost $59 and Brent almost $65.
Recently, Bloomberg reported, citing insiders, that repair work on oil facilities in Saudi Arabia after the attack in mid-September is progressing faster than expected. Accordingly, the production volume has reached a volume of eight million barrels per day and is moving back towards the original volume.
Recently, there have been several press reports citing insiders who report rapid progress being made by the state oil company Saudi Aramco in the repair work. However, commodity experts pointed out that Saudi Aramco is currently planning an IPO and wants to avoid negative headlines.
At the same time, there were some signs of easing in the conflict between Iran and Western countries: the British oil tanker &quot;Stena Impero&quot; is on its way to leave the port more than two months after being seized by Iran and the recent release. The crew is now preparing for departure while the ship is still at anchor, shipping company boss Erik Hånell told Swedish radio on Friday morning in an SMS.
However, the United States announced that it would transfer missiles and soldiers to Iran&#39;s archenemy in Saudi Arabia. Fears of an escalation between the Islamic Republic and countries such as the USA and Great Britain had at times pushed up oil prices significantly in the past few weeks.
